Claimant Count and Universal Credit in Trafford

Claimant Count in Trafford

The Claimant Count indicates the number of people claiming benefits principally for the reason of being unemployed. The Claimant Count in August 2023 was 29.3% higher than in January 2020. The rate of claimants to residents aged 16 to 64 reached 3% in August 2023 representing an increment of 0.7% from January 2020. The number of claimants has been decreasing from April 2021 but started to increase again from January to April 2023 and at similar level since May 2023.

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford compared to January 2020

The Trafford MSOA with the largest share of claims in August 2023 was Old Trafford with 13.8% of all claimants within Trafford, almost the double of claims than Gorse Hill, the MSOA with the second largest number of claims. 11 MSOAs out of 28 have more claims in August 2023 compared to August 2022. Old Trafford have the largest increase in number of claims with 70 more, followed by Broadheath & Firsway (25). Lostock & Stretford Meadows has the largest reduction in number of claims with 40 less, followed by Trafford Park West & Kingsway Park (-20), Stretford East (-20) and Sale North (-20).

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford's MSOAs

The MSOAs with higher claimant rate in August 2023 were Old Trafford with 7.7%, Partington with 5.8%, Gorse Hill with 5.7% and Firswood with 4.9%. From the top 4 MSOAs with the highest rates, Old Trafford and Firswood had a higher rate when comparing August 2022 to August 2023. The MSOAs where the claimant rate have decreased more from August 2022 to August 2023 are Lostock & Stretford Meadows with a decrease in rate of -0.9%, Trafford Park West & Kingsway Park with -0.4% followed by Stretford East with -0.4%, Sale North with -0.4% and Ashton upon Mersey North with -0.4%.

In Trafford from August 2022 to August 2023 3 age bands has increased the number of claimants, the age band 18 to 24 had the most increase with 65 more. When considering the reduction of claims the age band 60-64 years had the largest reduction with -50 less claims.

Change in the Claimant Count by age bands in Trafford
Change in the Claimant Count by broad age bands in Trafford

At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 already had the highest number of claims, however after the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic which started in March 2020 this figure increased more sharply compared to the other age bands. The claimant rate as a proportion of Trafford’s population within each age band showed then a higher increase in the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34 compared to the others. From January 2023 the count and rate of all age bands started to increase but the figures are fluctuating from April 2023.

More than half of Trafford’s claimants are residents of 7 of the 28 MSOAs. More than half of the claimants are between 25 and 40 years.

Claimant Count for Trafford's MSOAs by age band

Universal Credit claims in Trafford

The Universal Credit claims in Trafford have increased 87% from January 2020 to August 2023. The rate of claims as a proportion of people age 16 to 64 increased form 6.1% to 11.5% from January 2020 to August 2023.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford

The Trafford MSOA with the largest share of claims in August 2023 was Old Trafford with 12% of all Universal Credit claims in Trafford. 22 out of the 28 MSOAs have more claims in August 2023 compared to August 2022. The MSOAs with more additional claims when comparing August 2022 to August 2023 were Broadheath & Firsway (146), Old Trafford (129) and Partington (116). The MSOAs with more increase in percentage change from August 2022 to August 2023 were Trafford Park East & Sevenways with 14% change, Urmston West with 14% change and Broadheath & Firsway with 14% change. The MSOAs with reductions in claims when comparing August 2022 to August 2023 are Trafford Park West & Kingsway Park (-13) and Sale North (-13). The MSOAs with reduction in percentage change from August 2022 to August 2023 were Trafford Park West & Kingsway Park with -3% change and Sale North with -3%.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford's MSOAs

The MSOAs with higher rates of Universal Credit claims in August 2023 were Partington with 29.5% and Old Trafford with 25.2%. The MSOAs where the rate of Universal Credit claims has increased more from August 2022 to August 2023 were Broadheath & Firsway with 2.4% and Partington with 2.3% increase. The MSOA where the rate of Universal Credit claims has decreased from August 2022 to August 2023 were Trafford Park West & Kingsway Park with -0.3% and Sale North with -0.2%.

In Trafford from August 2022 to August 2023 the Over 65 age band has the largest increment in percentage change of Universal Credit claims with 44%. When considering the number of additional claims from August 2022 to August 2023 the 5-year age band 40-44 years had the highest with 219 more claims. The age bands 25-29 had a decrease in number of Universal Credit claims.

Change in the Universal Credit claims by age band for Trafford

Following the start of the Covid-19 pandemic in March 2020 the number of claims for all ages rose dramatically from pre-pandemic levels at a similar proportion for all age bands with the age band 16-24 rising faster in May 2020. At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 had the highest number of claims and also the highest rate maintaining that position after the rise from March 2020 until May 2022 when the 35-44 became the age band with the highest number of claims. The age band 16-24 has the lowest number of claims among the other age bands from July 2021. All the age bands are increasing their number of claims particularly from January 2023.

The Conditionality regimen for entitlement to Universal Credit is associated to work-related things that claimants will have to do to maintain eligibility. In Trafford the largest proportion of Universal Credit claims are in the “No work requirements” category however there is also a significant proportion of claims under “Searching for work”. In Old Trafford, 34% of Universal Credit claimants were under “No work requirements” whilst 30% where “Searching for work”. In Partington, 45% of claims were under “No work requirements” whilst 20% of claims were under “Working - no requirements”, and 19% under “Searching for work”.

Claimants continue to move across from legacy benefits to Universal credit therefore, the number of claimants with no work requirements continue to grow. In August 2023, 37.2% (6204) of claims in Trafford were under “No work requirements”, 24.6% (4104) were under “Searching for work”, 19.3% (3216) were under “Working - no requirements”, 12.2% (2029) were under “Working - with requirements”, 5.2% (863) were under “Preparing for work”, and 1.5% (249) where under “Planning for work”.
